  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions is complex and has evolved significantly over the past century. Here's an overview of key developments:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Historically, laws against hiding the proceeds of criminal activity existed in various forms\n- The term \"money laundering\" emerged during the Prohibition era in the United States (1920s-1930s)\n- Organized crime groups would disguise illegal income through cash-intensive businesses\n\n2. Initial Anti-Money Laundering (AML) Legislation:\n- United States passed the Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) in 1970\n- First comprehensive legislation requiring financial institutions to report large cash transactions\n- Aimed to help track potential criminal financial activities\n\n3. International Developments:\n- 1989: Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established\n- Created international standards for combating money laundering\n- Developed comprehensive recommendations for national legal frameworks\n\n4. Major Expansion Post-9/11:\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001) significantly expanded money laundering regulations\n- Increased reporting requirements\n- Enhanced international cooperation against financial crimes\n\n5. Ongoing Global Trend:\n- Continuous expansion of legal frameworks\n- Growing focus on cryptocurrency and digital financial transactions\n- Increasing international collaboration and standardization\n\nThis progression reflects growing global recognition of money laundering as a serious financial crime.",
